• Instagram's native save feature offers zero organisation. All saved content lives in a  single undifferentiated list. 
• As the list grows, retrieval requires scrolling — which triggers the same dopamine loop as  the main feed, leading to unintended doom-scrolling within saved content. • Short-form video is increasingly how people learn about products, routines, and  recommendations. But this knowledge is trapped in a format that is difficult to search,  reference, or synthesise. 
• There is no tool today that treats a user's saved reel library as a structured knowledge  base that can be queried conversationally. 
2.2 Target User 
• Primary: GenZ and millennial Instagram users who regularly save lifestyle content  (skincare, haircare, fitness, nutrition, fashion, AI/tech). 
• These users are already curators — they save content intentionally. ReelMind makes that  curation useful. 
• Secondary: Any user who uses saved content as a personal reference library across any  category. 
3. Goals & Non-Goals 
3.1 MVP Goals 
• Enable frictionless reel saving via the share sheet — zero new UX steps added to the  user's current behaviour. 
• Auto-categorise saved reels into lifestyle categories (skincare, haircare, bodycare, fitness,  nutrition, fashion) using AI — no manual tagging required. 
• Allow users to query their saved library using natural language, per category and globally. • Return answers as a chat-style response with rich cards linking back to the original reel. • Pre-process all content at save time so query responses are fast (< 3 seconds). 
3.2 Non-Goals (MVP) 
• Multi-platform support (TikTok, YouTube Shorts, Pinterest) — Instagram only for MVP. • Private Instagram account support — public reels only for MVP. 
• Price comparison engine (Nykaa, Flas.io integrations) — future scope. • Social/sharing features — this is a personal library, not a community product. • Web app — mobile app only for MVP. 
